<i>derivatives: </i><b>arjaka</b> &#xa0;<b>-arjya</b> <sub>C. </sub>&#xa0;<b>arjana</b> <sub>E.+ </sub>&#xa0;<b>arjanīya</b> <sub>C. </sub>&#xa0;<b>-arjayitṛ</b> <sub>C. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjipyá</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjíśvan</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjīpín</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjīṣá</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjūnas</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>-ṛṅga</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjīyas</b> <sub>V. </sub>&#xa0;<b>ṛjú</b> <sub>V.+ </sub>&#xa0;<b>ráji</b> <sub>RV. </sub>&#xa0;<b>rájiṣṭha</b> <sub>RV.B. </sub>&#xa0;<b>rajīyas</b> <sub>JB. </sub>&#xa0;<b>rāji</b> <sub>AV.+ </sub>&#xa0;</p><p>
It seems impossible to divide these forms (generally distributed to two different roots) from one another.  The root has three well-marked stages of develoment: <b>ṛj</b> or <b>ṛñj</b> in Rv., <b>arj</b> in Brah., and <b>arjaya</b> in the later languge.  Compare also &#x221a;<b>rāj</b>, probably a derivative from it.  With it is related, further, the anomalously formed stem <b>irajya</b> (<b>irajyáti</b> -<b>te</b> etc. RV., and <b>irajyú</b> RV.), 'direct, rule'.</p></body>
